---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';
import { STATES, getAllStateSlugs, getStateBySlug } from '../data/state-meta';

const title = `Property Tax Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}: Estimate by State & County`;
const description = `Calculate your ${TAX_YEAR} property tax by state and county. Compare effective property tax rates across all 50 US states and find exemptions with our free tool.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How is property tax calculated?',
    answer: `Property tax is calculated by multiplying your home's assessed value by the local tax rate (mill rate). For example, a home assessed at $300,000 with a 1.5% effective rate would owe $4,500 annually. Assessed value may differ from market value depending on your state's assessment ratio.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the average property tax rate in the US?',
    answer: `The national average effective property tax rate is approximately 1.1% of a home's assessed value. However, rates vary widely — from as low as 0.31% in Hawaii to over 2.2% in New Jersey. Local rates within a state can also vary significantly by county and municipality.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is a homestead exemption?',
    answer: `A homestead exemption reduces the taxable value of your primary residence, lowering your property tax bill. Most states offer some form of homestead exemption, ranging from a fixed dollar amount (e.g., $25,000 off assessed value) to a percentage reduction. You typically must apply and meet residency requirements.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I deduct property taxes on my federal return?',
    answer: `Yes, property taxes are deductible on your federal income tax return if you itemize deductions. However, the ${TAX_YEAR} SALT (State and Local Tax) deduction is capped at $10,000 for single filers and married filing jointly, which includes both property and income/sales taxes combined.`,
  },
];

const stateEntries = Object.entries(STATES)
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, ...s }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-navy-50 to-white px-4 pb-8 pt-10 dark:from-slate-900 dark:to-slate-950 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl text-center">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-white">
        Property Tax Calculator {TAX_YEAR}
      </h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-4 max-w-2xl text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
        Calculate your property tax by state and county. Compare effective rates across all 50 states and DC.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- State selector -->
  <section class="px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-800">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Estimate Your Property Tax</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
          Select your state below to see property tax rates, county-level breakdowns, and homestead exemption details.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- State grid -->
  <section class="px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl">
      <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        Property Tax by State
      </h2>
      <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-4">
        {stateEntries.map((s) => (
          <a
            href={`/property-tax-calculator/${s.slug}/`}
            class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-navy-300 hover:bg-navy-50 hover:text-navy-700 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-300 dark:hover:border-navy-600 dark:hover:bg-slate-700 dark:hover:text-navy-400"
          >
            {s.name}
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content -->
  <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 id="understanding-property-taxes">Understanding How Property Taxes Work in the United States</h2>
      <p>
        Property taxes are one of the oldest forms of taxation in America, predating the federal income tax by more than a century, and they remain the single most important source of revenue for local governments across the country. Unlike income taxes, which are collected by the federal government and most states, property taxes are administered almost entirely at the local level by counties, municipalities, school districts, and special taxing authorities. This local structure means that property tax rates, assessment methods, and available exemptions vary enormously not just from state to state, but from one county to the next within the same state. Understanding how this system works is essential for any homeowner or prospective buyer, because property taxes represent a significant and ongoing cost of homeownership that directly affects both your monthly budget and the long-term financial return on your real estate investment.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-property-taxes-assessed">How Property Taxes Are Assessed and Calculated</h2>
      <p>
        The property tax you owe is fundamentally the product of two numbers: the assessed value of your property and the tax rate applied to that value. The assessed value is determined by your local tax assessor, a government official whose job is to estimate the market value of every taxable property within their jurisdiction. Assessors typically use a combination of methods to arrive at this figure, including analyzing recent sales of comparable properties in your neighborhood, evaluating the replacement cost of the structure minus depreciation, and in the case of commercial or rental properties, examining the income the property generates.
      </p>
      <p>
        In many states, the assessed value is not the same as the full market value. States use what is known as an assessment ratio or assessment level, which is the percentage of market value that is subject to taxation. For example, if your home has a market value of $400,000 and your state applies an assessment ratio of 80 percent, your assessed value would be $320,000. Some states assess at full market value while others use ratios as low as 4 or 10 percent, which can make rate comparisons between states confusing without understanding the underlying assessment methodology. This is why financial experts prefer to compare effective property tax rates, which express the total tax paid as a percentage of the property's full market value, regardless of the assessment ratio used.
      </p>
      <p>
        Assessments are typically conducted on a regular cycle, though the frequency varies by jurisdiction. Some counties reassess every year, while others reassess every two, three, or even five years. In between assessment years, some jurisdictions apply automatic adjustment factors to account for general market movements. The timing of assessments can have significant implications for homeowners. If your county reassesses during a period of rapid appreciation, your tax bill could jump dramatically. Conversely, if property values decline and your county does not reassess for several years, you could be paying taxes based on an inflated valuation.
      </p>

      <h2 id="millage-rates-explained">Millage Rates and How They Determine Your Tax Bill</h2>
      <p>
        The tax rate applied to your assessed value is commonly expressed as a millage rate, or mill rate, where one mill equals one-tenth of one cent, or one dollar of tax per one thousand dollars of assessed value. A mill rate of 25 mills, for instance, means you pay $25 for every $1,000 of assessed value, which translates to an effective rate of 2.5 percent. Your total mill rate is actually the sum of several overlapping rates levied by different taxing authorities, each with its own budget and rate-setting process.
      </p>
      <p>
        A typical property tax bill includes levies from the county government, the municipal or city government, the local school district, and potentially additional special districts for things like libraries, fire protection, park maintenance, and water management. The school district portion is usually the largest single component, often accounting for 40 to 60 percent of the total bill. This is why homes in areas with highly rated public schools tend to carry higher property taxes, and it is also why you may see significant tax differences between two neighboring properties that sit in different school districts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each taxing authority sets its own rate through its annual budget process, which typically involves public hearings where residents can comment. The rates are set to generate the revenue needed to cover the authority's approved budget, minus any other revenue sources like fees and state aid. When property values rise across a jurisdiction, the taxing authority may reduce the mill rate while still collecting the same total revenue. Conversely, when values decline, rates may increase to maintain revenue levels. This dynamic is important because rising property values do not automatically mean higher tax bills, though in practice, many jurisdictions do capture a portion of appreciation-driven revenue growth.
      </p>

      <h2 id="property-tax-exemptions">Property Tax Exemptions: Homestead, Senior, and Veteran Programs</h2>
      <p>
        Most states and many local jurisdictions offer property tax exemptions that can significantly reduce your tax burden, but you typically must apply for them proactively. The most common is the homestead exemption, which reduces the taxable value of your primary residence by a fixed dollar amount or percentage. Florida, for example, offers a homestead exemption of up to $50,000 off the assessed value, which on a home assessed at $300,000 would reduce the taxable amount to $250,000. Texas offers a $100,000 homestead exemption for school district taxes. These exemptions are available only on your primary residence, not on second homes, rental properties, or vacant land.
      </p>
      <p>
        Senior citizen exemptions provide additional relief for homeowners above a certain age, typically 65. These can take the form of further assessed value reductions, tax freezes that lock your bill at its current level regardless of future value increases, or tax deferrals that allow seniors on fixed incomes to postpone payment until the property is sold. Veteran and disabled veteran exemptions are similarly generous in many states, with some states offering complete property tax exemptions for veterans with service-connected disabilities rated at 100 percent.
      </p>
      <p>
        Other less well-known exemptions exist for agricultural properties, properties in historic districts, properties with renewable energy installations, and properties owned by certain nonprofit organizations. If you believe you qualify for any exemption, contact your local assessor's office or county tax collector to verify eligibility requirements and application deadlines. Missing the application deadline, which is often in the first quarter of the calendar year, can mean forfeiting the exemption for an entire tax year. Also be aware that some states require annual renewal of exemptions while others are granted permanently once approved.
      </p>

      <h2 id="property-taxes-fund-local-services">How Property Taxes Fund the Services Around You</h2>
      <p>
        Property taxes are the financial backbone of local government services, and understanding where the money goes can help put your tax bill in perspective. Public education is by far the largest recipient, with school districts consuming the plurality or majority of property tax revenue in nearly every jurisdiction. This revenue funds teacher salaries, school construction and maintenance, classroom materials, transportation, and extracurricular programs. The heavy reliance on property taxes for school funding is also why educational quality varies so dramatically between wealthy and lower-income neighborhoods, a disparity that has been the subject of legal challenges in many states.
      </p>
      <p>
        Beyond education, property taxes fund police and fire protection, road maintenance, parks and recreation facilities, public libraries, water and sewer infrastructure, and local government administration. In communities with limited commercial tax base, residential property owners shoulder a disproportionate share of these costs. Conversely, areas with significant commercial or industrial properties benefit from a broader tax base that spreads the burden. This is one reason why communities actively recruit commercial development, as it generates tax revenue without placing the same demand on residential services like schools and parks that commercial properties do.
      </p>

      <h2 id="appealing-property-tax-assessment">How to Appeal Your Property Tax Assessment</h2>
      <p>
        If you believe your property's assessed value is too high, you have the right to appeal, and doing so successfully can reduce your tax bill for years to come. The appeal process varies by jurisdiction but generally begins with an informal review where you present evidence to the assessor's office that the valuation is inaccurate. Strong evidence includes recent sales of comparable properties in your neighborhood that sold for less than your assessed value, documentation of structural issues or needed repairs that diminish your property's value, or proof that the assessor used incorrect information such as wrong square footage, an incorrect number of bedrooms or bathrooms, or a missed condition issue.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the informal review does not resolve the dispute, you can file a formal appeal with your local board of review or assessment appeals board. This typically involves a hearing where you present your case, and the board may adjust the assessment, uphold it, or in rare cases, increase it. Many homeowners successfully reduce their assessments by 5 to 15 percent through the appeals process, which translates to meaningful annual savings. Some jurisdictions allow further appeal to a state-level board or to the courts if you are unsatisfied with the local outcome. Property tax attorneys and consultants can handle the appeal process for you, typically for a fee contingent on the tax savings achieved.
      </p>

      <h2 id="states-highest-lowest-property-taxes">States With the Highest and Lowest Property Taxes</h2>
      <p>
        Property tax rates across the United States cover an enormous range, and where you live has a dramatic impact on your total cost of homeownership. New Jersey consistently holds the top position with an effective rate averaging around 2.2 percent, meaning the owner of a $400,000 home in New Jersey pays roughly $8,800 per year in property taxes. Illinois, Connecticut, New Hampshire, Vermont, and Texas also rank among the highest, with effective rates generally above 1.6 percent. In Texas, the absence of a state income tax is partially offset by property tax rates that frequently exceed 2 percent in major metro areas.
      </p>
      <p>
        At the other end of the spectrum, Hawaii has the lowest effective rate at approximately 0.31 percent, followed by Alabama, Colorado, Louisiana, and South Carolina, all of which have effective rates below 0.6 percent. However, low property tax rates do not necessarily mean low overall tax burdens. States with low property taxes often compensate with higher income taxes, sales taxes, or both. Hawaii, for example, has a top marginal income tax rate above 10 percent, which more than offsets its low property taxes for high earners. Use our <a href="/">paycheck calculator</a> to see how income taxes affect your take-home pay in any state.
      </p>

      <h2 id="property-tax-and-home-values">The Relationship Between Property Tax and Home Values</h2>
      <p>
        Property taxes and home values exist in a complex bidirectional relationship that is important for both buyers and current homeowners to understand. On one hand, higher property values lead to higher assessed values and, therefore, higher tax bills, all else being equal. On the other hand, the services funded by property taxes, particularly school quality, directly influence home values. Research consistently shows that homes in top-rated school districts command price premiums of 10 to 20 percent or more compared to otherwise similar homes in lower-rated districts, even though the higher property taxes partially offset that premium.
      </p>
      <p>
        For prospective buyers, this means that choosing a home in a lower-tax jurisdiction does not always save money in the long run. A home in a well-funded district with good schools, maintained infrastructure, and responsive public services may appreciate more robustly than a comparable home in a jurisdiction where low taxes have led to deteriorating schools and services. The annual property tax cost should be weighed against the potential for stronger appreciation and better quality of life. Compare total housing costs including property taxes across locations using our <a href="/mortgage-affordability-calculator/">mortgage affordability calculator</a>, and factor in quality of life differences using the <a href="/cost-of-living-calculator/">cost of living calculator</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ultimately, property taxes are an inescapable part of homeownership in the United States, and they deserve the same careful analysis you would give to your mortgage interest rate or down payment amount. They cannot be refinanced, they tend to increase over time, and they continue for as long as you own the property, even after the mortgage is fully paid off. Factoring property taxes into your homebuying budget from the very beginning ensures that you will not be caught off guard by a cost that, in many areas, rivals or exceeds the interest portion of your mortgage payment.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQs -->
  <section class="px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>
      <dl class="space-y-6">
        {faqs.map((faq) => (
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 p-6 dark:border-slate-700">
            <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">{faq.question}</dt>
            <dd class="mt-2 text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">{faq.answer}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
